Report: Analysis of SHAP (SHapley Additive exPlanations) on wine_quality Dataset¶

Dataset¶

The wine_quality dataset comprises 11 continuous variables that describe various wine features. Notably, there exists a significant class imbalance, with 4715 instances of one class compared to 183 of the other, resulting in a disproportion of roughly 25.77 times.

Models¶

The models evaluated in this analysis are as follows:

  • RandomForestClassifier
  • XGBClassifier

Samples¶

I choose two samples from test dataset one of id 45 and another 72, respective labels are 0 and 1. I will use those two data points to check shap of both models: RandomForestClassifier and XGBClassifier.

Task A¶

Library dalex¶

Dalex library offers a lot ot possible plots and comparisons of shapley values.

The Dalex library provides various plots and comparisons for Shapley values. In the initial Shapley Values plot, we observe distinct feature influences on different labels. For both samples, volatile_acidity is the most influential, with potential negative and positive effects (5. from homework). However, in the case of sample 45, density emerges as the second most influential feature, while it doesn't even rank in the top 9 for the other sample. For the other sample, residual_sugar assumes the second most influential position.

Library shap¶

Now, shifting our focus to the Shap library. Examining the waterfall plots reveals results akin to the Dalex library.

In the first sample, most features exert a negative influence. Interestingly, volatile_acidity, which was initially the top influencer, is surpassed by free_sulfur_dioxide. In the second plot, residual_sugar takes the lead in contribution, highlighting variations across samples (4. homework).

Libraries comparison¶

In comparing both libraries, they offer extensive insights and flexibility for experimentation. Discrepancies in results may arise from Shap's non-deterministic nature. While Dalex is deemed easier to use and interpret, Shap provides a deeper level of insight and flexibility in analysis. The choice between them might depend on the specific needs and preferences of the user.

Testing another model - Random Forrest Classifier¶

In this final experiment, we're comparing Shap values between two different models: XGBoost Classifier and Random Forest Classifier. There are four plots, two for each model, corresponding to each label. For the first sample (negative label), we observe that Random Forest Classifier (RFC) strongly emphasizes pH, which wasn't a significant contributor for XGBoost. Additionally, a key contributor for XGBoost, density, is absent in RFC (7. homework). Another noteworthy observation is that, for the first sample, features have the same sign of contribution across both models. In plots 3 and 4, the contributions of both models appear similar, with both identifying residual_sugar as the most influential factor.

Task B¶

Given following values

v() = 0
v(A) = 20
v(B) = 20
v(C) = 60
v(A,B) = 60
v(A,C) = 70
v(B,C) = 70
v(A,B,C) = 100

Let's calculate marginal contributions for player A.

$$ (I) C_{A} - C_{0} = 20 - 0 = 20 $$$$ (II) C_{AB} - C_{B} = 60 - 20 = 40 $$$$ (III) C_{AC} - C_{C} = 70 - 60 = 10 $$$$ (IV) C_{ABC} - C_{BC} = 100 - 70 = 30 $$

Since we can arrange players A, B and C on 3! = 6 ways we can calculate probabilities that change is made by player A (First arrange players from previous coalition then insert player A):

$$ (I) P = \frac{1! 2!}{3!} = \frac{1}{3} $$$$ (II) P = \frac{1! 1!}{3!} = \frac{1}{6} $$$$ (III) P = \frac{1! 1!}{3!} = \frac{1}{6} $$$$ (IV) P = \frac{2! 1!}{3!} = \frac{1}{3} $$

So Finally $$ \varphi_A = \frac{20}{3} + \frac{40}{6} + \frac{10}{6} + \frac{30}{3} = \frac{150}{6} = 25 $$
